04379nam a22006375i 9780520940802DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209408027 a10.1525/97805209408022doi  a(DE-B1597)519467  a(OCoLC)61730535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML275b.F75 2005eb 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780/.943/090342221 aFrisch, Walter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGerman Modernism :bMusic and the Arts /cWalter Frisch. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 20th-Century Music ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Ambivalent Modernism -- tTwo. German Naturalism -- tThree. Convergences -- tFour. Bach, Regeneration, And Historicist Modernism -- tFive. Ironic Germans -- tSix. "Dancing In Chains" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this pioneering, erudite study of a pivotal era in the arts, Walter Frisch examines music and its relationship to early modernism in the Austro-German sphere. Seeking to explore the period on its own terms, Frisch questions the common assumption that works created from the later 1870s through World War I were transitional between late romanticism and high modernism. Drawing on a wide range of examples across different media, he establishes a cultural and intellectual context for late Richard Wagner, Richard Strauss, Gustav Mahler, and Arnold Schoenberg, as well as their less familiar contemporaries Eugen d'Albert, Hans Pfitzner, Max Reger, Max von Schillings, and Franz Schreker.Frisch explores "ambivalent" modernism in the last quarter of the nineteenth century as reflected in the attitudes of, and relationship between, Nietzsche and Wagner. He goes on to examine how naturalism, the first self-conscious movement of German modernism, intersected with musical values and practices of the day. He proposes convergences between music and the visual arts in the works of Brahms, Max Klinger, Schoenberg, and Kandinsky. Frisch also explains how, near the turn of the century, composers drew inspiration and techniques from music of the past-the Renaissance, Bach, Mozart, and Wagner. Finally, he demonstrates how irony became a key strategy in the novels and novellas of Thomas Mann, the symphonies of Mahler, and the operas of Strauss and Hofmannsthal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArt and musicxGermany. 0aArt and music. 0aModernism (Art)xGermany. 0aModernism (Art)zGermany. 0aModernism (Music)xGermany. 0aModernism (Music)zGermany. 0aMusicxHistory and criticismx19th centuryxGermany. 0aMusicxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxGermany. 0aMusiczGermanyy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczGermanyy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520940802.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles